  <div class="timeline-comment-wrapper js-comment-container">
    <a href="/collinmurray"><img alt="@collinmurray" class="timeline-comment-avatar" height="48" src="https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/1314499?v=3&amp;s=96" width="48" /></a>
    <div id="issue-30019490"
     class="comment previewable-edit timeline-comment js-comment js-task-list-container "
     data-body-version="138f93ee0f079319c545df983c68fcbb">

  <div class="timeline-comment-header ">




  <div class="timeline-comment-header-text">

    <strong>
      <a href="/collinmurray" class="author">collinmurray</a>
    </strong>

    commented

    <a href="#issue-30019490" class="timestamp">
      <time datetime="2014-03-24T09:40:23Z" is="relative-time">Mar 24, 2014</time>
    </a>
  </div>
</div>


  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="comment-body markdown-body markdown-format js-comment-body">
          <p>Hi Sean</p>

<p>Currently your android implementation (IntentIntegrator) takes an Activity as an argument and it's startActivityForResult() method is called on the Activity you pass it. This is fine when it's that activity calling the scanning intent, but becomes a bit messy when calling the scanner from a fragment. The resulting onActivityResult() call is handled first by the Activity, as per the android activity lifecycle. (Activity.startActivityForResult()...)</p>

<p>In my case, the Activity is housing multiple Fragments and it's a bit messy when passing down the results.</p>

<p>My question is this: Is there a way to call and return on a fragment in the existing codebase? I stumbled on code by Lachezars in 2012 which was removed from trunk that supported V4 fragments. It's basically just a wrapper that overrides startActivityForResult() and I updated it to handle android.app.Fragment. Is this perhaps the correct thing to do, or should i leave it alone to avoid copyright issues?</p>

<p>I have gone through the google discussion held in 2012, but i'm worried the code being removed from trunk might indicate i'm missing something for current fragment support.</p>

<p>Reference: </p>

<p>IntentIntegratorSupportV4 <a href="https://code.google.com/p/zxing/source/browse/trunk/android-integration/src/com/google/zxing/integration/android/IntentIntegratorSupportV4.java?r=2122">https://code.google.com/p/zxing/source/browse/trunk/android-integration/src/com/google/zxing/integration/android/IntentIntegratorSupportV4.java?r=2122</a></p>

<p>Old Google Discussion<br>
<a href="https://code.google.com/p/zxing/issues/detail?id=1323">https://code.google.com/p/zxing/issues/detail?id=1323</a></p>

<p>PS: Thanks for the great support on ZXing. Definitely my favorite barcode app. I've been reading your comments on multiple sites about integration vs intent/separate app. While i'm not too happy having a 2nd app requirement, I understand and respect your reasoning and have implemented it as per your preference. Keep up the great work.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

  </div>
  <div class="timeline-comment-wrapper js-comment-container">
    <a href="/srowen"><img alt="@srowen" class="timeline-comment-avatar" height="48" src="https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/822522?v=3&amp;s=96" width="48" /></a>
